:"1359–1446","1307–1347":"1307–1347","1304–1344":"1304–1344","1359":"1359","1304":"1304","1347":"1347","1446":"1446","1335":"1335","1344":"1344","1421":"1421","28 February 1347":"28 February 1347","1390":"1390","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland":"Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Moray in northeastern Scotland, which derives from Celtic <i>mori-</i> ‘sea’ + <i>treb-</i> ‘settlement’. The founder of the Scottish house of Murray was a Fleming named Freskin who was granted Strathbrock in West Lothian and Duffus in Moray by David I. The family took its name from the region in the late 12th century.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of   McMurray  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muireadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muireadhach</i>’ a personal name meaning ‘mariner’. Occasionally it may be a shortened form of   McMurray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murri","meanings":["Probably Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murry","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murrah","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","Scottish: habitational name from Murie in Errol (Perthshire).","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Merhi","meanings":["Arabic (mainly Lebanon and Syria): from a variant of the personal name <i>Mirhi</i> of unknown meaning. Bearers of this surname are both Muslims and Christians. Compare   Murray   5."]},{"name":"Murrey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"McMurray","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muireadhaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muireadhaich</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘seafarer’ (see   Murdoch  ). Compare   McCurry   1."]},{"name":"Murra","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): topographic name from Sicilian <i>murra</i> ‘large rock, mass of rocks’ or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","East Frisian: unexplained.","Albanian: nickname from <i>murrë</i> (definite form <i>murra</i>) ‘dark gray cow’."]},{"name":"Murrie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Murray was born in 1335, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, John Murray - Fourth Lord of Tullibardine, was 28 and his mother, Mary Stewart de Menteith, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Le Baird. He died in 1390, in Perthshire, Scotland, at the age of 55, and was buried in Tullibardine, Perthshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1335–1390":"1335–1390","1328–1421":"1328–1421","1359–1446":"1359–1446","1307–1347":"1307–1347","1304–1344":"1304–1344","1359":"1359","1304":"1304","1347":"1347","1446":"1446","1335":"1335","1344":"1344","1421":"1421","28 February 1347":"28. veebruar 1347","1390":"1390","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Tullibardine, Perths